answer.en:
### WeakRef + FinalizationRegistry — Optional Caching Without Memory Leaks

```javascript
// --- WeakRef: hold a reference that doesn't prevent GC ---
let largeData = { content: new Array(100000).fill('data') };
const weakRef = new WeakRef(largeData);

console.log(weakRef.deref()?.content.length); // 100000

largeData = null; // remove strong reference
// After GC runs (indeterminate timing):
// weakRef.deref() returns undefined

// --- FinalizationRegistry: get notified when object is GC'd ---
const registry = new FinalizationRegistry((heldValue) => {
  console.log(`Object associated with "${heldValue}" was garbage collected`);
});

let obj = { id: 1 };
registry.register(obj, 'obj-cleanup-token');
obj = null; // now eligible for GC
// Eventually: 'Object associated with "obj-cleanup-token" was garbage collected'

// --- Practical: optional in-memory cache that doesn't cause leaks ---
class OptionalCache {
  #cache = new Map();
  #registry;

  constructor() {
    this.#registry = new FinalizationRegistry((key) => {
      this.#cache.delete(key);
      console.log(`Cache entry for "${key}" evicted by GC`);
    });
  }

  set(key, value) {
    this.#cache.set(key, new WeakRef(value));
    this.#registry.register(value, key);
  }

  get(key) {
    const ref = this.#cache.get(key);
    if (!ref) return undefined;
    const value = ref.deref();
    if (!value) {
      this.#cache.delete(key); // clean up stale entry
      return undefined;
    }
    return value;
  }
}

const cache = new OptionalCache();
let user = { id: 42, name: 'Alice' };
cache.set('user:42', user);

console.log(cache.get('user:42')?.name); // 'Alice'
user = null; // GC may evict; cache.get('user:42') may return undefined
```

**Common interview trap:** `WeakRef.deref()` always returns `undefined` if the object was GC'd — never the original reference. You **must** check the return value before using it. Also, the FinalizationRegistry callback is called on a separate microtask after GC, not synchronously, and the timing is non-deterministic. Never rely on it for critical logic — only use it for opportunistic cleanup.

