### Event Loop — Complete Cycle with Rendering

Understanding the full event loop cycle explains why certain animations stutter and when exactly `requestAnimationFrame` runs.

```javascript
// --- Full event loop cycle order ---
// 1. Execute current task (macrotask)
// 2. Drain microtask queue completely
// 3. Perform rendering steps (if needed):
//    a. resize/scroll handlers
//    b. requestAnimationFrame callbacks
//    c. IntersectionObserver callbacks
//    d. paint
// 4. Execute idle callbacks (requestIdleCallback)
// 5. Pick next macrotask → go to step 1

console.log('task: sync');

setTimeout(() => console.log('task: setTimeout'), 0);

requestAnimationFrame(() => {
  console.log('rAF: runs just before paint');
  // Good place to: update DOM, measure layout
});

Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('microtask: Promise'));

queueMicrotask(() => console.log('microtask: queueMicrotask'));

console.log('task: sync end');

// ORDER:
// task: sync
// task: sync end
// microtask: Promise           ← microtask queue drained
// microtask: queueMicrotask
// rAF: runs just before paint  ← rendering step
// task: setTimeout             ← next event loop iteration

// --- Why this matters for performance ---
function badAnimation() {
  // Reading layout, then writing: forces reflow on every frame
  const height = element.offsetHeight; // read → triggers reflow
  element.style.height = height + 1 + 'px'; // write
}

function goodAnimation() {
  requestAnimationFrame(() => {
    // All reads first, then all writes
    const height = element.offsetHeight;
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      element.style.height = height + 1 + 'px'; // write after read
    });
  });
}

// --- MessageChannel as a "fast macrotask" (used by React scheduler) ---
// MessageChannel fires faster than setTimeout (no 4ms minimum)
const { port1, port2 } = new MessageChannel();
port1.onmessage = () => console.log('message channel task');
port2.postMessage(null);
// Runs as a macrotask but with less delay than setTimeout
```

**Common interview trap:** `requestAnimationFrame` is NOT a microtask — it's part of the **rendering step** of the event loop, which runs after microtasks but before the next macrotask. This is why `rAF` callbacks see a consistent DOM state (all microtasks from the previous task have already run). Also, if you never request a frame (headless environment, tab in background), `rAF` may never fire.

